       (ChatDBG lldb) frame variable                                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
                                                                                
                                                                                
    The crash is caused by a use-after-free in destroy_list.                    
                                                                                
    In main, the list is built like this:                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     Node *c = new Node{3, nullptr};                                            
     Node *b = new Node{2, c};                                                  
     Node *a = new Node{1, b};                                                  
     destroy_list(a);                                                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
    So the list state before destroy_list(a) is:                                
                                                                                
                                                                                
     a -> b -> c -> nullptr                                                     
                                                                                
                                                                                
    with:                                                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     a->value == 1, a->next == b                                                
     b->value == 2, b->next == c                                                
     c->value == 3, c->next == nullptr                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    The bug is here:                                                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
     for (Node *cur = head; cur != nullptr; cur = cur->next) {                  
         delete cur;                                                            
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    The loop deletes cur, then the for loop update expression runs:             
                                                                                
                                                                                
     cur = cur->next                                                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
    But at that point cur points to memory that has already been freed by       
    delete cur. Reading cur->next is therefore a use of deallocated memory.     
                                                                                
    Step-by-step:                                                               
                                                                                
     1 cur is initialized to head, which is a.                                  
     2 cur != nullptr is true.                                                  
     3 The loop body executes:                                                  
                                                                                
        delete cur;                                                             
                                                                                
       This frees node a.                                                       
     4 The loop update expression executes:                                     
                                                                                
        cur = cur->next;                                                        
                                                                                
       But cur still has the old pointer value for a, and a has already been    
       deleted. Reading cur->next dereferences freed memory.                    
                                                                                
    That is exactly what AddressSanitizer reports: a load of the next pointer   
    from deallocated memory at line 12.                                         
                                                                                
    The immediate defect is that the code deletes the current node before       
    saving the pointer to the next node.                                        
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
    Minimal local fix in                                                        
    /Users/ibraheemamin/projects/COS484/chatdbgpro/bench/cases/uaf-linked-lis…  
    line 12:                                                                    
                                                                                
    Replace:                                                                    
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void destroy_list(Node *head) {                                     
         for (Node *cur = head; cur != nullptr; cur = cur->next) {              
             delete cur;                                                        
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    with:                                                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void destroy_list(Node *head) {                                     
         for (Node *cur = head; cur != nullptr; ) {                             
             Node *next = cur->next;                                            
             delete cur;                                                        
             cur = next;                                                        
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    or equivalently:                                                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void destroy_list(Node *head) {                                     
         while (head != nullptr) {                                              
             Node *next = head->next;                                           
             delete head;                                                       
             head = next;                                                       
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    The important part is that next is read before delete cur.                  
                                                                                
    A more thorough root-cause fix would be to avoid raw owning pointers and    
    manual deletion entirely. For example, model ownership with                 
    std::unique_ptr:                                                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <cstdio>                                                          
     #include <memory>                                                          
                                                                                
     struct Node {                                                              
         int value;                                                             
         std::unique_ptr<Node> next;                                            
     };                                                                         
                                                                                
     int main() {                                                               
         auto c = std::make_unique<Node>(Node{3, nullptr});                     
         auto b = std::make_unique<Node>(Node{2, std::move(c)});                
         auto a = std::make_unique<Node>(Node{1, std::move(b)});                
                                                                                
         std::printf("done\n");                                                 
         return 0;                                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Then the list is destroyed automatically when a goes out of scope, and      
    there is no need for destroy_list or manual delete.                         
                                                                                
